NOTE     "synopsis": "\"The Middle Way View\"\n\nBrief Teaching and Practice on the Dudjom Tersar Ngondro\nwith Lama Dragpa\n\nSaturday, November 6\n3:30-5:30pm EDT\n\n\n--\n\n\nFood for Thought for Lama Dragpa\u2019s unabashedly Buddhist talk on \u201cThe Middle Way View\u201d on Saturday, Nov. 6th from 3:30-5:30pm, which will also include a full practice of the Dudjom Tersar Ngondro.\n\n\nI love swimming in the deep end of the Buddhadharma\u2014in fact, Vajrayana practice assumes that this is where we\u2019re hanging out in order for our practice to stay on track.\n\n\nSo reviewing key points is always helpful for me. Hopefully it will be helpful for you too!\n\n\nEveryone\u2019s warmly welcome. I\u2019ll walk through this deep topic systemically, point by point, one step at a time. Enjoy!\n\n\nThere are 3 mutually-supportive ways of understanding and performing emptiness.\n\n\n1. Second Turning of Rangtong\n(qualitative emptiness of intrinsic existence)\n+\n2. Third Turning of Shentong\n(\u201csubstantive\u201d ground of all being)\n+\n3. Vajrayana and Dzogchen\n(postconceptual \u201c4th time\u201d)\n=\nmore fully integrated lineage approach to emptiness\n\n\nEach approach to emptiness offers a key, distinct function that cannot be omitted without compromising important 9 yana insight to thoroughly bake the cake of enlightenment.\n\n\nHere\u2019s a quick connection that might be interesting to think about in terms of reframing the 3 ways of understanding and performing emptiness.\n\n\nAccording to certain Nyingma lineage Mahayoga pith instructions for practicing the Union of Creation and Completion Stages, there are 3 key points that have to be simultaneously performed and verified in one\u2019s personal experience for one\u2019s practice to be \u201cauthentic,\u201d or to bring swift results: (1) clarity (salwa), (2) purity (dagpa), and (3) stability or fearlessness (tanpa).\n\n\nTo some degree, these 3 points correlate with framing emptiness as simultaneously being a quality, \u201csubstance,\u201d and nonconceptual awareness. If these aren\u2019t simultaneously enacted (due to mastery), at least none of them can be conceptually omitted without reducing the 3-D complexity of emptiness into 2-D or 1-D over-simplifications that omit big, vital chucks of Dharma and distort fundamental contributions of the Nyingma practice lineage of the Inner Tantras.\n\n\n1. Clarity: intricate particulars of one\u2019s visualization (representation) of substantial features of the container and the contained (the apparent \u201cthe world\u201d such as bodies, environment, and oneself) which gradually becomes a direct seeing of pure relative truth as one\u2019s concepts become more accurate, and eventually included within a larger scope of post-conceptual wisdom awareness that allows subject-object duality to arise, but without reifying appearances into exclusive binaries, but rather accommodates them as inclusive polarities that are integrated from this \u201chigher,\u201d more comprehensive \u201cwisdom\u201d awareness.\n\n\n2. Purity: the quality of lacking inherent true existence (quality), or alternatively, abiding in nonconceptual wisdom awareness that doesn\u2019t reify experience even as it allows percepts and concepts to emerge (as wisdom display, or tsal)\n\n\n3. Stability: Unwavering conviction or certainty wisdom that stably, one-pointedly remains in nonconceptual wisdom with \u201cvajra pride\u201d without attaching to or avoiding the natural arising energy of the nature of mind.\n\n\nSo in a way, from the Inner Tantric practice that eventually leads to direct yogic perception (or the fourth time, which always already includes these 3 other performances of emptiness) . . .\n\n\nClarity: emptiness as apparent \u201csubstance\u201d or \u201cground\u201d\n\n\nPurity: as the pure quality of this groundless ground when it\u2019s not reified\n\n\nStability: abiding in non-reifying, nonconceptual awareness that still allows for all the other accurate ways of mind to function, while it also clearly knows the deluded, distorted, fixated ways the mind functions having been there and done that, without needing to collapse into that mode presently.\n\n\nSimply put, we experience everything (the world; the ground) as pure display (emptiness-appearance; groundless) with nonconceptual wisdom (emptiness-awareness; unframed).\n\n\nThis means \u201cit\u2019s all always already transcendental wisdom rainbow body,\u201d yet allows plenty of (conceptual and experiential) space for mistaken nightmares of samsaric vision to happen throughout sentient interpretations of time and space.\n\n\nwww.padmasambhava.org",
